# The "build context" is everything in this directory that `docker build`
# reads and sends to the Docker daemon before a single instruction runs (it's
# why `docker build` always prints "Sending build context to Docker daemon
# ...MB" as its first line). By default that's EVERY file under this
# directory, walked recursively — .dockerignore trims that set, the same way
# .gitignore trims what `git add` considers, and using the exact same
# glob-pattern syntax.
#
# Two independent reasons this matters here, not just one:
#   1. Speed/size: the larger the context, the longer `docker build` takes
#      just to transfer it, before any instruction even executes.
#   2. Correctness: target/ contains this project's OWN previous build
#      output (compiled .class files, an already-built jar, a JaCoCo
#      report, from running `mvn` on the host). None of that should ever be
#      copied into the image — the Dockerfile's whole job is to rebuild all
#      of that from source *inside* the controlled build stage, so the
#      image's contents are reproducible from source, not accidentally
#      contaminated by whatever stale artifacts happen to be sitting on the
#      developer's machine at build time.
target/

# Version control metadata. Irrelevant to the running application and
# potentially large (full commit history) — never has a reason to be inside
# a build context or shipped image.
.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# Editor/IDE-specific files (matches the entries already ignored by the
# repo-root .gitignore) — machine-local, never relevant to a container build.
.vscode/

# This file itself doesn't need to be re-copied into the build context.
Dockerfile
.dockerignore
